    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/primary-hemolysis-cfd-experiment-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary CFD–experiment hemolysis index comparison across 5 VAD operating points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis-dataset",
      "description": "A comprehensive validation campaign was conducted over 18 months comparing CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values against in-vitro measurements obtained from three independent laboratory runs of the FDA generic centrifugal pump operated under VAD conditions (flow rates 2–6 L/min, rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM). The CFD solver employed a power-law hemolysis damage model (Giersiepen–Wurzinger constants) coupled to Lagrangian particle tracking across 5000 representative fluid trajectories per operating point. Mesh sensitivity was confirmed via Richardson extrapolation on three grid levels (4.1 M, 11.2 M, and 28.7 M cells). Experimental NIH values were corrected for background hemolysis using a paired saline control. Across all five operating points the model predicted NIH within ±22% of the experimental mean, with the largest deviation at the lowest flow rate (2 L/min, 2000 RPM) where recirculation zones amplify shear-exposure uncertainty. Monte Carlo sampling (n=2000) over inlet velocity, fluid viscosity, and damage-model constants yielded 95th-percentile prediction intervals that enclosed the experimental observations at four of five points. The fifth point fell marginally outside the 95th-percentile bound; sensitivity analysis identified the Giersiepen–Wurzinger exponent as the dominant contributor. Despite this exceedance, the absolute NIH values remained below the clinical hemolysis threshold of 0.01 g/100 L across all sampled parameter combinations, supporting the acceptance decision. Full tabular results, raw experimental records, and Monte Carlo sample archives are retained in the project data repository."
    },
